<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 7:13<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If5ca96f16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I358217d0933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>7.</label.designator><headtext>Selection of a Transferee Judge</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94f968e3e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>7:13.</label.designator><headtext>Assignment of successor judge</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel may be called upon to transfer cases to another judge if a transferee judge cannot continue to serve for any reason. <eos/><bos/>The Panel may do so if the original transferee judge dies,[<footnote.reference refid="If5ca96f26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] is removed from the case, or recuses himself or herself for any reason.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If5cabe006b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] The Panel has assigned successor judges in these circumstances on the motion of the judge.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If5cabe016b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] A party could also move the Panel for reassignment in any of these circumstances.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel&apos;s authority to name a successor judge is exclusive to the Panel. <eos/><bos/>In one case the assigned transferee judge, acting as Chief Judge of the transferee district, reassigned the cases to a different judge of the district. <eos/><bos/>The court of appeals, in reviewing the class certification ruling of the new judge, determined that the judge did not lack jurisdiction over the subject matter, although he was acting <ital>ultra vires</ital> in ruling on the motions.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If5cabe026b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If5ca96f16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If5ca96f26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914097" w-serial-number="2013122556" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000344" ID="I646bc6c16b3e11e984eaf7fbfa3d7525">In re Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., Inc. Research Reports Securities Litigation, 246 F.R.D. 156 (S.D. N.Y. 2007)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If5cabe006b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The removal of judges from a case is beyond the scope of this book. <eos/><bos/>It is discussed in greater detail in <csc>David F. Herr, Roger S. Haydock &amp; Jeffrey W. Stempel, Motion Practice</csc>§ 19.2 (8th ed. 2019).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If5cabe016b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914097" w-serial-number="1978124041" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="390" ID="I646cb1216b3e11e984eaf7fbfa3d7525">In re South Central States Bakery Products Antitrust Litigation, 462 F. Supp. 388, 390 (J.P.M.L. 1978)</cite.query> (recusal).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If5cabe026b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914097" w-serial-number="2033751500" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="I646d74716b3e11e984eaf7fbfa3d7525">In re IKO Roofing Shingle Products Liability Litigation, 757 F.3d 599 (7th Cir. 2014)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 7:13<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
